512. notos atque...in nubila ‘off to the south winds and the black clouds '. This is sometimes called anastrophe of the preposition : where there are two phrases conjoined the latter only having the prep. which is therefore supposed to take efflet backwards.

The real fact is no doubt that originally the case expresses the relation required generally, the prep. only defining it more specifically. Thus in lIomer. we find ἢ ἁλὸς ἢ επὶ ’γῆςς and it is not right to say ἐπὶ governs άλοςε ἁλὸς expresses the place where vaguely, ἐπὶ ’γῆς the place whereon.

This use once established, an artificial poet like Vergil will put the first of two nouns without a preposition in cases where only the appear- ance of the preposition with the second can justify it.
